<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99836317195257></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99836317195257><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99836317195257>RE: Why?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99836317195257#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=72364><span id= >Camthorn</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>10 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Aug 20th 11:06 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Here is my attempt at answering the why. It's a cop-out for many of the posters, but the difference in when you posted your original thread and when I am responding is a indicator.<br><br>EQ is a moving target.  <br><br>Let me clarify that a little. I'm a big fan of doing research on anything I undertake that I've had zero experience with before.  Usually I don't do this with games, especially RPGs, but I had to make an exception with EQ. I played my first character, a human monk, to about level 12 without looking up maps, hitting this site, etc. I found all the creatures on my own, figured out how groups work, and had a little bit of input from a co-worker who has been playing for a couple of years.  I had deliberately abstained from EQ when it first came out because I was in college and didn't want to flunk all my classes.(of course now I'm missing sleep at night and my wife gets mad and my boss frowns at me when I come in a couple hours late, but they'll get over it :)   <br><br>Anyway, what convinced me that I needed to start visiting these "spoiler" sites?  Random meaningless death.  Once in the form of a camp of ogres that were in WK(two harm touches for 291, dead). I got a port to WK and tried to run to Qeynos Hills. I asked someone what the loc of the zone to QH was and started off for it.  I learned never to go overland in zones you don't know, but looking back the road was just as dangerous for a lvl 12 newbie.  Ok, so I learned my lesson right? I buy a port this time(costing most of my money, about 12 platinum at the time.  As a monk I don't need much cash right?  Well that's the theory. Jewelry is expensive and very, very good to have. And don't get me started on weapons or the overhead in getting your trade skills up. When was the last time you saw a Mob drop a packet of Kiola sap?)  <br><br>Back to the story, learned my lesson, paid the price in plat to go back and get my body. Going to get a bind as soon as I reach Qeynos.  Get ported to NK this time.  Get directions to the ROAD TO THE WK border(see, I do learn).  Head off towards the road. CRUNCH!  Hill Giant.  Loading please wait.<br><br>ARRRGGHHHH!  The Freeport newbie zone is a nice place, but at level 12(now nearly lvl 11, :(  ) it starts to lose it's appeal.  So I say @#%^ it. I hit eqatlas, I hit allakhazams and then I buy ANOTHER port to NK and beg a very nice druid to SoW and Invis me and escort me to my body and to bind me in Qeynos.  <br><br>Now I read about a zone extensively before I set foot in it. I print out the maps and have them handy, I study the guides and ask tons of questions about how to play my character(get the best I can afford now and have to upgrade in a few levels or save up a ton of money and twink myself with high-level stuff ahead of my time?) Sure there is a "roleplayers" way of doing things, and if this was D&D I wouldn't even ask if I could skip ahead to that jewelry the lvl 50s wear at lvl 20.  But EQ is different.  I have to continually ask questions and research the game, partly because it's so complex, but mainly because it's so random.  I got killed three times in the newbie zone in Freeport when a rare spawn necromancer wandered up from the sewers and fear kited me around the area while her pet whooped up on me(fscking gaurds just stood there and watched).  Unfortunately I was bound in FP and spawned right next to her again, and again.  <br><br>To make this a little more relevant, and to stop the whiny-bitchy-newbie mode, let's look at why someone would ask the same question over and over.<br><br>Monk weight limits.  Originally anytime a monk went over 14 stone they suffered AC penalties, big time at high levels.  Let's look at how the early messages on this board say to get around that.<br><br>Sewing kits.  The weight has changed on the large sewing kits and the deluxe don't drop at all anymore.<br>Wait until high level.  I don't know if this ever materialized.  I have heard that the weight limit goes up as your level increases, but my information, from monkly-business, tells me that it increases 1 stone per 15 levels. Which means that I can carry 15 stone at lvl 18 without penalty.  I have heard other interpretations as well. <br><br>Now on to fists versus weapons.  Originally fists ruled. Kunark changed that. Then the epic changed it again. Now the top 1HB weapons(like Wu's Fist of Mastery) are better than fists again for many things.<br><br>What about Instill Doubt?  Does it use kick or not?  Can you raise it on corpses/boats?  Goes back and forth apparently.  Depends on who you ask.<br><br>This information has changed.  Research isn't as valuable anymore.  Asking someone about what is true NOW is what is valuable.  Unfortunately this means the long-suffering answer-givers are overloaded.  I'm sorry guys.  I've been you, and I'm still you on other subjects in other forums. But in order to survive in this game, I have to continually ask what you might consider a dumb question or one which you have already answered, simply because it might have changed.<br><br>Steven<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
